The villagers realized the truth: Veythas had used them. But the Hollow King, though enraged, could not strike directly—his curse required a **willing hand**. So he whispered to the villagers, *‘If you seek justice, you must give what he took.’* The villagers, though poor, pooled their last coins to buy a **silver chain**, forged in the blacksmith’s fire. They lured Veythas with promises of a greater treasure, then bound him with the chain, which burned like ice against his fur.

The Hollow King emerged, his hollow eyes gleaming. *‘You took my voice,’* he rasped. *‘Now you will carry it.’* With a skeletal finger, he pressed the Crown of Whispers onto Veythas’ head. The fox screamed as the crown fused to his skull, forcing him to **repeat every lie he ever told**, his voice a chorus of deceit. The villagers, horrified, banished him to the woods, where he still wanders—his once-silver tongue now a curse, his betrayals echoing endlessly.

